fields.name: Blacksod Point Lighthouse
fields.description: A lighthouse designed (1863) by John Swan Sloane (c.1823?-96), Superintendent of Foremen and Works for the Ballast Board, and a familiar landmark on the tip of the Mullet Peninsula. As a navigational aid the lighthouse facilitated safe entry into a treacherous harbour that had seen La Rata Santa Maria Encoronada, a ship of the Spanish Armada, run aground in 1588.  As a weather station the lighthouse also proved invaluable during the Second World War (1939-45). Photograph by John Kelly courtesy of the Commissioners of Irish Lights

fields.name: Lisnavagh House
fields.description: Lisnavagh House, County Carlow, which was one of the largest houses in Ireland before its owners, the Bunburys, orchestrated a major reduction in the 1950s. Photograph by James Fennell

fields.name: Thatched House, BALLYGARRAN
fields.description: The only surviving thatched house in the village of Kilmuckridge, County Wexford, it is located in a prominent position directly opposite the Catholic church. It is not known when exactly the house was constructed, but it is clearly indicated on the Ordnance Survey map published in 1841 along with three other houses which formed a cluster around the church and national school. There are now no visible remains of the other houses or the school. The first known inhabitants of our house were Patrick and Mary Redmond – the great, great, great grandparents of our children – who took up residence in the 1860s and were both teachers in the national school. On their retirement, their daughter Margaret Redmond took over as teacher and remained living in the cottage until she died in 1974. The restoration of the house was assisted by grants from the Heritage Council and Wexford County Council through the Built Heritage Jobs Leverage Scheme 2014 and is now home of the heirs of the original owners.
